<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> CharTech: Aragorn<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9034'>David "Turambar" F</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9034&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 26, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> This is the first in a series of articles on my website that is directed towards <u>newbies</u> in assisting in the choice of which companions to use, and which version therein. For more information, please visit my site at <a href=&quot;http://twilightpool.netfirms.com/&quot;>http://twilightpool.netfirms.com/</a> (hmm, is it legal to add that reference?). Constructive comments appreciated.<br>
<br>
-----------------<br>
<br>
Arguably the most popular companion out there, Aragorn is highly usable because of his versatility and his tendency to be at the centre of most decks, most notably King in Exile. A look at the different versions out there:<br>
<br>
Aragorn, King in Exile (Premium, FotR)<br>
Twilight: 4<br>
STR: 8<br>
VIT: 4<br>
Aragorn signet<br>
Companion - Man<br>
Ranger<br>
At the start of each of your turns, you may heal another companion who has the Aragorn signet.<br>
The engine that keeps most decks together, the King in Exile is often the most important companion in fellowships based around rangers, elves and men, because he takes on an important and almost singular role: that of healing the fellowship. In many fellowships is he the only healing mechanism in place.<br>
<br>
A quick glance around reveals the following companions with the Aragorn signet: Arwen - Daughter of Elrond, Boromir - Lord of Gondor, Gandalf, the Grey Pilgrim - Frodo, Reluctant Adventurer - Merry, From O&#39;er the Brandywine, Pippin - Mr. Took, Sam - Son of Hamfast, Gimli - Dwarf of Erebor, Legolas - Son of Thrandûil.<br>
<br>
His spectrum is broad. Arwen and Boromir are companions often found in Ranger-Elf decks and he is the means by which their vitality is sustained. Gandalf would not be such a competent alternative to Friend of the Shirefolk if he did not have the Aragorn signet to heal, assisting him to cancel skirmishes with his Staff, exert for Glamdring and Sleep etc. Frodo, Reluctant Adventurer is almost a staple in decks which do not utilise Hobbit allies, largely because of his solid text and Aragorn signet. Sam, Son of Hamfast&#39;s ability is unique in that he requires the King in Exile to allow him to remove the ringbearer&#39;s burdens consistently and without restrictions. As for Legolas, the key for him is that his exertions for The Splendor of Their Banners can be healed off with Aragorn.<br>
<br>
As can be seen, useful companions all possess the Aragorn signet, and their usefulness often stems from the signet itself. It is not surprising that a large number of companions these days all possess the Aragorn signet with Aragorn the key to keeping them alive. Care must be taken, however, not to rely too much on him. If faced with an accidental death, loosely-constructed fellowships can crumble apart without their healer and leader, evidencing his strong influence.<br>
<br>
Aragorn, Ranger of the North (Rare, FotR)<br>
Twilight: 4<br>
STR: 8<br>
VIT: 4<br>
Gandalf signet<br>
Companion - Man<br>
Ranger<br>
Maneuver: Exert Aragorn to make him defender +1 until the regroup phase.<br>
<br>
The choice between Ranger of the North and King in Exile is a hard one as both have their strengths. For a deck which does not need to depend on the Aragorn-signet heal however and can heal by other means, Ranger of the North is definitely a viable choice. The direct means to protect the ring-bearer from an overwhelm is to direct minions away from him and Aragorn is the pinnacle of this, taking on minions to lessen the pressure on the ring-bearer.<br>
Ranger of the North is more of a throw-in companion in totally unrelated decks to take the responsibility of an expendable companion. However, unlike others in the same vein, like Pippin and Thrarin, Aragorn gets to take it for the team by skirmishing the maximum number of minions to guarantee the survival of the fellowship. To make it simple, a fully-healed Ranger of the North at Site 9 is almost an auto-win (except against Sauron). Care, however, has to be taken that he justifies his 4-twilight cost when used in this way.<br>
<br>
<b>Analysis:</b><br>
As can be seen, Aragorn is a vital chain in the link that binds the fellowship together, especially King in Exile. Yet, not only does he prevent or cure other companions from harm, he too is more than capable of protecting himself. He has the highest printed strength on him and contains 4 vitality, which is the maximum for the fellowship un-boosted (which incidentally he can boost with The Saga of Elendil). He bears the Ranger keyword in addition to his Gondor Man status, which opens him up to card options like No Stranger to the Shadows, The Last Alliance of Elves and Men, Athelas, A Ranger&#39;s Versatility, The Saga of Elendil, Flaming Brand and a lot more. Also, he has some of the best possessions in the game. Ranger&#39;s Sword is average but Aragorn&#39;s Bow is almost essential in every deck which utilises Aragorn (though less so with Ranger of the North), allowing him to pick off key minions before they get to do any harm. Not surprisingly, Aragorn often bears the most possessions and conditions in the fellowship, and these not only benefit him, but the fellowship in general.<br>
<br>
Another amazing tool which compounds his usefulness is that he can be easily &quot;downloaded&quot;. Starting him is never a wise choice as he would be a single starting companion and unlike Gandalf, there are no benefits to be reaped from it. Drawing into him too is also a bad choice as a high number of cards have to be borne or at least spot him. It is therefore a blessing that Site 1 offers the option of The Prancing Pony, which allows you to add a burden to play Aragorn from your draw deck. Aragorn&#39;s powerful ability has turned this site into the most overwhelmingly popular Site 1 out there (and also the bane of most decks when they are denied it), and allows the key companion of the fellowship to enter play early and lead on. In fact, the popularity of The Prancing Pony can be evidenced by how the few decks which do not need Aragorn like Dwarves throw in a copy of Aragorn, Ranger of the North just to take advantage of the Pony&#39;s text.<br>
<br>
True to the book, Aragorn has been crafted into one of the most important companions out there which justifies his appearance in almost every deck currently.<br>
<br>
<b>Final Verdict:</b><br>
Plays Well With Others: 10/10<br>
King in Exile can be slotted into virtually any deck and take on a centrepiece role except those that centre around Dwarves and Hobbits. Even then, Ranger of the North can serve as a useful expendable companion in those decks. <br>
<br>
Importance: 9/10<br>
In most decks, he is second only to Gandalf in terms of importance with his immense number of support cards and precious healing ability with King in Exile. In fact, in decks which use The Grey Pilgrim instead, he is the main man in the fellowship. Case in point: try letting King in Exile die at Site 2.<br>
<br>
Value: 10/10<br>
Despite having the tied highest twilight cost of 4 to deploy, he more than sufficiently justifies his set-up cost with his powerful tools that aid the fellowship. Not to mention how the overwhelming availability of The Prancing Pony allows him to be set up early, when shadow danger is low. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3727&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
